<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-06-12T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-06-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="385" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d385">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/1244</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at London</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRP1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-06-12">
                                        <hi rend="italic">June 12, 1915</hi>.</date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 10.30 a. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Department’s 11th. Goods originating Belgium are presumptively enemy
                                origin and it lies upon those interested to prove that Germany would
                                not profit from intended operation. In practice this is difficult to
                                prove, as Belgian representatives not in position to ascertain
                                material facts. Am assured each case will be considered upon merits
                                and whenever it can be demonstrated that transaction is for benefit
                                Belgians, to exclusion of German advantage permission will be
                                granted.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_SRP1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Skinner</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>